Comment: Last night's game in the Oxford & Didtrict League's knockout competition, the Frank Wood Shield.  We got a strange position out of the opening, after which White applied some pressure for a while but eventually cracked under time pressure.  There's a rather comical ending too ...

!? Normally, when faced with a later d4 than usual, I try to transpose into a
normal open Sicilian but this time I decided to embarrass her bishop first,
offering the opportunity to swap a piece for two pawns, creating remote passed
pawns as compensation.

?! She took the bait.  I'm not sure she gets sufficient compensation.  If she
does, she didn't exploit it effectively ...

Now Black's position looks very odd: wide open spaces on the Q-side and a
completely undeveloped kingside.  I had to think hard over the next few moves
to manage my development while avoiding threats and traps.

Although I wanted to get my minor pieces out quickly, I couldn't find a safe
way to do so immediately.  I was worried about 9...Ngf6 10. e5 dxe5 11. dxe5,
when I'd have to move the attacked N again.  Swapping now on d4 reduced that
risk but gave my opponent a second remote passed pawn and allowed her N to take
up a threatening position, with c6 undefended allowing further disruption.

This surprised me as I'd been concentrating on how I would respond to 11. Qf3
or 11. f4 or 11. Bg5.  It seemed solid enough but didn't seem to threaten to
disrupt my development.

However, on further consideration, I decided that I couldn't proceed as
originally planned by playing  ...Be7 because of the unpleasant fork from c6.
Once my Q moved, he could just swap N for B and leave my K stuck on e7.

Another surprise: rather a timid looking move when I'd been expecting
aggression, though it looks more logical from White's viewpoint than it did
from where I sat.

Development completed without too much disruption.  Now I expected to be
preoccupied with stalling a queenside pawn storm ...

Apparently preparing to swap her active B for my inactive, fianchettoed B,
something I wouldn't have minded as I couldn't see a convincing follow-up for
her.

Played mainly to prevent her N from coming to c6.  A quick look at the
scoresheet and clocks enabled me to work out at this stage that I had moved
faster than a move a minute, whereas she had been averaging 3 minutes a move.
It was comforting to know that I would have plenty of time to plan my defence
and counter-attack.
Attacking the pawn on d6.

A triple purpose move, enabling my Q to defend d6, preparing to harrass her Q
from c4 or g4, and blockading White's e-pawn.
Preventing the more annoying option and perhaps commencing the pawn storm?
Attacking her N and unpinning the Nf6

Establishing a late form of the Maroczy Bind, which pegs my pawns back for  the
rest of the middle game.

Attacking her Q and preparing to open up the long diagonal, possibly combined
with a check with ...Ne5-f3 at some point.

Not entirely unexpected.  Swapping Qs at this point would have removed the
lynchpin of my defence and prepared the ground for the pawn advance.

So I side-stepped the swap, improving my Q's position and threatening her pawn
on e4.

Now my initial thought was to defend the pawn with 20 ...Ne8 but then 21. Be7
wins the exchange.
